\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To develop a framework,
 the current field of heterogeneous multi-robotic systems needs to be understood to ensure a significant impact in the literature.
 This section of the report will begin with a brief overview of Multi-robot SAR and the state-of-the-art systems that are being deployed.
 Given the nature of multi-robotics,
 many sub-systems need to be addressed and considered to fabricate a suitable framework.
 The following sections will briefly summarise the current methods and challenges in multi-robotics that are considered in the synchronous integration of all systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Disaster Robotics:
 Multi-Robot SAR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In disaster robotics,
 recent work by Peña Queralta et al.
 (2020) offers a comprehensive review of how multi-robot systems are currently supporting SAR operations.
 Their survey highlights collaborative deployments involving aerial,
 ground,
 surface,
 and underwater robots across various environments;
 urban,
 maritime,
 wilderness,
 and subterranean.
 While these projects demonstrate the benefits of using heterogeneous teams,
 they primarily focus on combinations of two locomotion types,
 such as UAVs paired with UGVs or Unmanned Surface Vehicles (USVs)/ Unmanned Underwater Vehicles (UUV).
 To date,
 there is no documented instance of an operational SAR system that incorporates all four major locomotion types in a coordinated fleet,
 especially with the more complicated locomotion method of a legged walker vehicle,
 such as a bipedal robot or quadruped.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite strong advances in system design and coordination,
 the current state of SAR robotics often relies on centralized decision-making and predefined task allocation.
 Projects like ICARUS,
 NIFTi,
 and TRADR have shown effective collaboration between aerial and ground units,
 and the DARPA SubT Challenge has pushed forward multi-domain autonomy.
 However,
 these efforts are still limited in scope and often constrained by the operating environments or hardware capabilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This meta-study examines the causes and characteristics of field failures in unmanned ground vehicles (UGVs) used in urban search and rescue (USAR) and military operations.
 Drawing on ten field studies covering 15 UGV models,
 the paper introduces a comprehensive taxonomy of failure types—
spanning physical faults (e.g.,
 control systems,
 effectors) and human factors—
and finds that most failures are terminal but field-repairable,
 with mean time between failures ranging from 6 to 20 hours.
 The analysis highlights the need for improved reliability through robust design,
 realistic field testing,
 and closer integration of end-user feedback in development.This gap highlights a clear opportunity for research into fully integrated,
 domain-spanning robot fleets capable of operating cohesively in complex,
 multi-modal disaster zones.
 https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/1435486
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study presents a fully autonomous quadrotor system for urban search and rescue (USAR),
 capable of navigating both indoor and outdoor environments without GPS or external computation.
 By combining laser and stereo vision odometry with onboard processing,
 the UAV can adapt to changing conditions and maintain accurate localization.
 The system’s effectiveness was demonstrated through autonomous flight trials in constrained environments,
 including indoor-to-outdoor transitions.
 https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/6290694
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Algorithms for Risk assessment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defining the term traversability as the ability for a robot or autonomous vehicle to navigate through an environment safely [define traverse],
 clarify the need for traversability risk assessments in the framework.
 This work will encompass all variety of risks in the taxonomy,
 including traversability-based and efficiency-based risk;
 traversability-based is classified as physical elements such as terrain elevation,
 the grounds fitness to a plane (roughness) and obstacles that hinder movement,
 compared to the communication loss and battery consumption in efficiency-based.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Traversability-Based Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current characterisation of traversability risks is split into sensor-based and map-based characterisation.
 Sensor-based approaches use sensors to communicate potential risks to agents,
 which is mainly seen in applications of fundamental obstacle avoidance and off-road navigation.
 Early navigation methods used a concept of instant goals in a globally convergent path planning system where the risk of collision was characterised as the minimum distance to an obstacle from a range finder.
 Many other navigation and model predictive control algorithms generate a restricted path for an autonomous vehicle to follow based on the obstacle representations,
 ensuring a boundary is inaccessible and reducing collisions.
 []
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively,
 the sliding mode control law proposed in [] establishes pre-set distances from the obstacle boundary that are maintained.
 The risk is characterised by the sliding surface,
 not the obstacles (a function of length).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another form of risk definition involves collision ellipsoids,
 which form circles of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 around the main robot and other agents,
 limiting the likelihood that the centres of the machines cross into a different ellipsoid.
 This method differs from deterministic path planning by introducing a chance constraint,
 ensuring the probability of agent collision does not exceed an upper bound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key terrain parameters have been considered in [],
 using sensors to create cohesion and internal friction angle parameters to estimate a robot traversability risk metric based on terrain shear strength.
 (Expand on)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sensors-based characterisation has been seen in more complex techniques,
 such as exponential utility functions,
 particle filtering models,
 and quantile regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The map-based characterisation of risks is an approach that uses an environmental map as input,
 providing terrain data from the camera,
 IMU,
 GPS,
 and LiDAR to depict terrains and their traversability.
 The primary map-based algorithm is the 2D Bayesian occupancy grid,
 modelling the environment as a probable grid of cells representing fragments of the environment whilst attaching a probabilistic variable of how likely the element in the grid is to be occupied.
 This estimate is updated based on the Bayesian filter,
 which considers each cell an individual entity.
 Voxel maps were introduced for 3D mapping applications representing volumes of space as a voxel element (3D pixel).
 However,
 these maps scaled poorly due to large memory requirements.
 Costly copy operations must be executed every time the map area is expanded due to the grid map being initialised in a bounding box regardless of actual distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other grid-based traversability maps have been used that exclude occupancy probability and focus on the possibility of the robot successfully driving over a terrain feature.
 These maps analyse a 2D probabilistic grid with multiple sensors to acquire more information,
 such as terrain slopes [].
 This was expanded as the authors constructed a traversability map that deployed three fundamental terrain characteristics:
 slope,
 curvature,
 and roughness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More practical mapping methods,
 such as 2.5D Digital Elevation Maps (DEM),
 expand on 2D mapping by storing the elevation of a cell instead of occupancy probability.
 Also known as Cartesian elevation maps,
 DEM is widely used for modelling and traversability analysis.
 However,
 they do not adequately represent vertical obstacles and multi-level structures,
 such as bridges and overhangs.
 This led to the development of multi-level surface (MLS) maps,
 allowing multiple variables in each cell that could depict multiple surfaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 voxel-based mapping approaches like the 3D grid and DEMs typically required a large amount of memory and significant assumptions about the corresponding environment,
 and it did not address the difference between free and unknown space.
 Octrees address these limitations by providing a memory-efficient,
 hierarchical 3D occupancy map.
 Since it is hierarchical,
 the tree can be cut at any level to obtain a coarser sub-division if inner nodes are maintained,
 such that the volume is recursively subdivided into eight sub-volumes until a given minimum voxel size is reached,
 determining the resolution.
 If a specific volume is measured as occupied,
 the corresponding node in the octree is initialised.
 Uninitialised nodes could be free space or unknown;
 this ambiguity is resolved by explicitly representing free volumes in the tree as the volumes between the sensor and the range end-point of a time-of-flight reading (via ray casting).
 Unknown areas are implicitly initialised.
 This use of boolean occupancy states allows for a compact representation of the structure,
 such that if all node children have the same state (occupied or free),
 they can be pruned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The OctoMap framework,
 derived from octrees,
 can be extended to enrich the map with additional terrain information at each voxel,
 such as colour and temperature,
 demonstrating the algorithm’s scalability.
 However,
 limited research has been undertaken to merge octomaps for multi-robotics applications due to the complexity and lack of support for global optimisation to fix mapping errors and odometry drift.
 Alternative mapping techniques such as Ski maps and real-time appearance-based maps (RTABMap) have faster updates and can fix odometry errors with updates,
 at the expense of being less efficient with larger maps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To more appropriately access risk,
 the Lambda field framework was developed to store the risks as a rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 ) of the likelihood that failure will occur in each cell at a given position.
 The risk function can be any risk associated with any risk that would lead to an agent’s termination,
 not just collisions,
 with more complicated extensions,
 presenting a new risk by considering a harmful event as a time to deform the wheel of the robot,
 calculating risk as a maximum potential energy absorbed by said wheel,
 such that each cell is measured by its the likelihood for the robot to traverse across it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear from the literature that for a concrete risk assessment of the environment,
 a mixture of sensor-based and map-based risk characterisation is needed to detect potential damage to the vehicle,
 thus inhibiting traversability.
 By fusing both characterisations,
 each robot agent will be able to interoperate its environment and be fully self-aware of the environmental risks by considering occupancy maps with other environmental risk attributes.
 Additionally,
 recent work has discussed environments with dynamic and occluded obstacles,
 which are definitive risk factors in the real world.
 (Expand on)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noteworthy frameworks,
 such as neural networks or machine learning approaches to dynamic traversability mapping,
 provide efficient segmentation of dynamic and static environmental zones.
 Unfortunately,
 the general drawback of neural networks is the dependency of the training data set on what the training step would teach the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Potential to extend this section by looking at locomotion-specific risk assessment characterisation)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Efficiency-Based Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond the obvious physical risks like rough terrain or obstacles,
 robots also face a range of non-physical challenges that can affect how well they perform.
 These are known as efficiency-based risks.
 While they might not cause a robot to crash or get stuck,
 they can still lead to mission failure by reducing performance,
 causing delays,
 or stopping a task altogether.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These kinds of risks are mostly tied to limited onboard resources,
 such as how much battery life a robot has left,
 how well it can process data,
 or whether it can stay in contact with the rest of the team.
 This is especially important in multi-robot systems used for things like search and rescue,
 where there's often no room for error.
 A robot might technically be able to keep moving,
 but if its battery dies,
 it loses signal,
 or its processor gets overloaded,
 it stops being useful or worse,
 it becomes a liability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some common examples of efficiency-based risks include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Battery depletion – The risk of a robot running out of power before finishing its task.
 This becomes more likely with long missions,
 challenging terrain,
 or heavy computing loads.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Communication loss – Losing connection with the fleet or base station,
 which is a big problem in places like tunnels or collapsed buildings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computational overload – When the robot has too much data to process in real time,
 which can cause it to make slow or bad decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
System fatigue or overuse – When a robot is pushed too hard or scheduled too often,
 leading to wear-and-tear or declining performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To deal with these risks,
 many systems now use predictive models that estimate how much power a robot will need or how likely it is to stay connected.
 For example,
 energy use can be predicted based on past data and terrain analysis,
 while communication dropouts might be predicted from known signal dead zones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some approaches use Bayesian inference or Markov models to estimate the chances of a failure happening,
 which can then be used to make smarter decisions about who does what in a robot team.
 These predictions help task planners assign jobs to the robots that are not only capable but also most likely to complete them without running into problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More advanced systems even plan for redundancy —
 assigning extra robots to key areas or avoiding risky zones if a robot’s battery is running low.
 In heterogeneous fleets,
 where robots differ in what they can do or how long they last,
 this kind of planning becomes even more important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though efficiency-based risks are not as visible as physical ones,
 they’re just as critical.
 Ignoring them can lead to poor performance,
 resource waste,
 or miscommunication between robots.
 Any solid multi-robot framework needs to look at both traversability and efficiency if it’s going to make smart,
 reliable decisions in complex environments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Risk Quantification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To quantify the risk in the preceding section,
 [] provided the Axiomatic Theory of Risk in Robotics,
 expanding on what constitutes a suitable risk metric.
 The six axioms for risk metrics in robotics are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
A1.
 Monotonicity:
 
\series default
Suppose there are two random cost variables tied to different robots A and B (
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'$
\end_inset

 respectively);
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'$
\end_inset

is guaranteed to be greater than or equal to a random cost 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'$
\end_inset

 must be deemed at least as risky as 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

;
 such that a robot would deposit at least the same amount resources,
 if not more,
 into the riskier task than the lesser task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
A2.
 Translation invariance:
 
\series default
For a random cost variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and a deterministic cost variable 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Z+c)=p(Z)+c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
A3.
 Positive Homogeneity:
 
\series default
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\beta\geq0$
\end_inset

 
\series default
be a scalar.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\beta Z)=\beta p(Z)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
A4.
 Subadditivity:
 
\series default
For two random cost variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'$
\end_inset

.
 Then the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Z+Z')\leq p(Z)+p(Z')$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
A5.
 Comonotone additivity:
 
\series default
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'$
\end_inset

 and comonotone,
 such that if two random costs rise and fall together,
 there is no benefit from diversifying.
 Supplementing A4,
 such that if one robot performs poorly at a task and another robot performs poorly on the same task,
 there is no benefit of using both robots simultaneously to reduce risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
A6.
 Law invariance:
 
\series default
The final axiom is if both 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'$
\end_inset

 are identically distributed,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Z)=p(Z')$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-28619-4_10
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantifying risks in robotics means assigning a numerical value to the uncertainty associated with possible adverse outcomes of a process.
 Substituting the abstract idea of risk for a measurement that could be controllable allows for evaluation algorithms for robot fleets to allocate tasks.
 Given the axioms above,
 standard practices such as mean-variance that captures both the average random value and variability (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}[X]+\beta Var[X]$
\end_inset

) can be seen as an incoherent risk metric as it does not comply with the law invariance (A6).
 On the contrary,
 the lambda field traversability risk does constitute a coherent metric satisfying all six axioms and the worst-case metric seen in [https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/9683744] as well,
 leading to the justification of an impactful and physical risk metric that could be extracted from path planning and be injected into a more significant role in decision-making for robotic fleets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cost maps are foundational in mobile robotics,
 representing the terrain,
 obstacle layout,
 and potential hazards in the environment.
 Traditionally used in path planning,
 these maps can be augmented with probabilistic risk models that consider the likelihood of adverse events (e.g.,
 slippage,
 collisions,
 or mechanical failure) across different regions.
 A risk-aware cost map might assign higher traversal costs to narrow,
 obstacle-dense zones not just based on geometry but on the probability of mission failure —
 creating a blended metric that guides planning under uncertainty.
 When aligned with axioms such as subadditivity and law invariance,
 these models avoid underestimating compound risks across multiple areas or robots.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Semantic Segmentation for Risk Interpretation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To better inform these cost maps,
 semantic segmentation using machine learning provides rich contextual understanding of the environment.
 Instead of treating an image or LiDAR scan as raw input,
 semantic segmentation classifies regions (e.g.,
 “mud,” “concrete,” “debris,” “open water”),
 allowing the risk model to account for terrain type and associated robot vulnerabilities.
 These contextual classes can be linked to empirically measured failure rates —
 for example,
 drones may associate "dense foliage" with signal loss,
 while ground robots may treat "loose gravel" as high-risk for traction.
 Such semantics drive risk metrics that are more task- and platform-specific,
 enabling fine-grained multi-robot decision-making.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Predictive Planning and Risk Extrapolation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Risk quantification also enables predictive planning,
 where robots extrapolate future risk based on current trends and models.
 Instead of planning only for immediate cost minimization,
 agents can use predictive tools —
 like Gaussian process regression or Bayesian forecasting —
 to model how the environment may change (e.g.,
 weather conditions,
 pedestrian density,
 or communication signal strength).
 These models can be encoded into time-evolving cost functions or risk distributions,
 giving robots the capacity to delay a task,
 reroute,
 or reassign missions to other fleet members.
 Importantly,
 predictive planning also supports robust coordination strategies,
 where risk trade-offs are made collectively across agents rather than in isolation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Localisation and Fleet Mapping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a robotic fleet to efficiently navigate through an unknown environment,
 the communication between each member and a shared perception of the environment is critical for accurate decision making,
 and individual robot path planning.
 A majority of autonomous mobile robots use simultaneous 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatives to OctoMaps,
 Voxels grids,
 point cloud,
 signed distance fields,
 represents surfaces implicitly,
 Truncated signed distance fields,
 used in 3d reconstruction,
 mesh based mapping uses triangular or polygonal meshes for detailed surface representation,
 elevation mapping,
 stores height data(Ground robots)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
__
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In multi-robot systems,
 the ability to accurately integrate local maps into a unified global representation is essential for coherent localisation,
 planning,
 and decision-making.
 A significant body of research has explored different strategies for 3D map merging,
 particularly when using octree-based representations like OctoMaps due to their efficiency in storing volumetric data.
 Drwięga et al.
 (2018) introduced a computationally optimised adaptation of the Iterative Closest Point (ICP) algorithm tailored for octomap integration.
 Their method bypasses the need for full point cloud reconstruction by directly aligning octree structures,
 enabling efficient and scalable fusion of partial maps generated by spatially distributed agents.
 This approach is particularly advantageous in large-scale or resource-constrained environments,
 where memory usage and processing time are critical constraints.
 However,
 ICP-based methods generally rely on a reasonable initial pose estimate to ensure convergence,
 limiting their robustness in unstructured or GPS-denied settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address these limitations,
 a follow-up study by the same author (Drwięga,
 2019) proposed a feature-matching approach that does not require prior knowledge of the robots’ relative poses.
 Instead,
 the method extracts local keypoints and descriptors from overlapping sections of octomaps,
 identifies correspondences using SHOT (Signature of Histograms of OrienTations),
 and estimates the transformation using a sample consensus algorithm,
 followed by local refinement via ICP.
 This hybrid strategy combines the strengths of both global feature alignment and local geometric optimisation,
 allowing for greater flexibility when robots explore disjointed or unknown areas.
 While computationally more demanding,
 this feature-based pipeline improves robustness in low-overlap scenarios and enables map merging even when inter-robot encounters do not occur in the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together,
 these contributions reflect the broader shift in multi-robot mapping research toward flexible,
 decentralised approaches that support autonomous exploration and robust localisation without dependency on centralised infrastructure or pre-calibrated initialisation.
 Their relevance spans domains from subterranean robotics to aerial and underwater mapping,
 where varying sensory modalities and inconsistent contact between agents necessitate map fusion techniques that are both adaptable and computationally tractable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Path Planning and Collision avoidance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Risk-Based Path Planning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Path planning for robots and autonomous mobile vehicles focuses on the map-based risk assessments so that the robot does not collide into obstacles and other physical risks in their environment.
 Therefore,
 the risk factor is the main driving component for robot navigation and fleet decision making.
 Starting with terrestrial mobile robots,
 traversability risk is assessed along a virtual paths which are superimposed onto metric maps or grids.
 By tessellating the environment into a grid of cells of a fixed size where inside the cell the field maintains constant,
 allows the environmental field denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $e:\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to be broken down an appropriately assess the occupation and variables of the field inside the cells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest function measures the occupancy cost of a list of cells in the grid (to form a path or trajectory).
 Occupancy being a binary classifier allows a reward to be assigned to each cell based on its occupancy status;
 positive values denoting occupied and negative denoting free space.
 Comparing the summed rewards of each path (list of cells) allows the robot to match the trajectory with the highest yielded reward to being the safest path to a predetermined goal.
 When considering the use of Bayesian occupancy grids the risk of traversing a path 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{|0,i|}$
\end_inset

 given by a set of i cells is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R(P_{|0,i|})=1-\prod_{j=0}^{i}(1-P_{j}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of occupancy within the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 cell.
 Other work shows the probabilistic definition of risk as the likelihood of the robot finishing the set path or trajectory in the map given as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R(P_{|0,i|})=1-\prod_{j=0}^{i}\prod_{k=0}^{r}(1-r_{k}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the probability an occupied cell 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to cause failures at position 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 given the history of the robot traversing cells from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Loss Functions and Physical Risk Metrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More appropriate solution were developed,
 due to limitations of the simple equations incorrectly evaluating the field in which the paths traversed,
 such as the work of [] which considered the risk of a path to be a measurement of expected loss,
 forming the loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $L(x_{v},x_{c})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{v}$
\end_inset

 is the vehicle state and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the cell state:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R(P)=\sum_{i=0}^{N-1}P_{i}\cdot L(x_{v},x_{c}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
defining the risk loss function as the total loss of kinetic energy in the system as the integral over the trajectory.
 In this formulation,
 the total risk along a path is expressed as the expected loss,
 weighted by the probability of encountering hazards in each cell.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is represented as kinetic energy,
 it carries physical meaning —
 unlike simpler models based on collision probability,
 which may yield values in the unbounded range [
\begin_inset Formula $0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 and lack a tangible interpretation.
 However,
 the function is sensitive to the map’s resolution:
 as the environment is tessellated into smaller cells,
 the number of contributing risk elements increases,
 artificially inflating the total.
 To compensate,
 a common workaround involves multiplying each cell’s risk by its area (
\begin_inset Formula $∆a$
\end_inset

),
 normalising the value relative to cell size.
 While this corrects for scaling,
 it weakens the original physical interpretation —
 transforming the risk from a real-world measure,
 such as force or energy,
 into a dimensionless quantity.
 This shift turns the metric into a heuristic that’s more abstract and less directly tied to measurable impacts on the robot,
 such as energy loss or mechanical wear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By contrast,
 the Lambda field framework preserves its physical consistency regardless of map resolution.
 Instead of summing over discrete cells,
 it defines risk as a continuous function over space —
 specifically,
 as the expected value of a failure-related metric integrated across the area the robot has traversed.
 This approach avoids the distortion caused by varying cell sizes,
 as the risk remains anchored to physical parameters like failure rate or the energy absorbed by robot components.
 As a result,
 the metric remains stable,
 interpretable,
 and better suited to applications requiring physically meaningful decisions,
 such as heterogeneous fleet coordination or real-time navigation through complex terrain.
 The expected value of a risk function 
\begin_inset Formula $r(a)$
\end_inset

 over a path is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[r(X)]=\intop_{p}f(a)r(a)da,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 denotes the area traversed and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a)$
\end_inset

 is the probability distribution across that space.
\end_layout

