\begin_layout Section
Communication and Coordination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent advances in multi-robot systems have enabled coordinated behaviours among fleets of unmanned robots across a range of applications,
 from warehouse automation to environmental monitoring and disaster response.
 At the heart of this capability lies multi-robot communication —
 the exchange of data,
 commands,
 and situational context between robots and control infrastructure.
 Research in this area focuses on building robust communication frameworks that can adapt to dynamic environments,
 manage limited bandwidth,
 and ensure timely and reliable message delivery despite network disruptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fleet coordination,
 closely tied to communication,
 addresses the challenges of task distribution,
 path planning,
 and decision-making across robot teams.
 Approaches range from centralized planning with global awareness to decentralized systems that rely on local observations and peer-to-peer communication.
 Current work explores trade-offs between scalability and control fidelity,
 often leveraging swarm intelligence,
 distributed optimization,
 and multi-agent reinforcement learning to enable robots to dynamically allocate tasks,
 avoid collisions,
 and adapt to environmental changes in real time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasingly,
 the integration of communication protocols with onboard autonomy is becoming essential,
 especially in contexts with intermittent connectivity or where human oversight is limited.
 Hybrid models that combine infrastructure-based and ad hoc communication are being tested in field robotics,
 such as autonomous vehicle fleets or heterogeneous teams of aerial and ground robots.
 These efforts aim to improve resilience,
 enable collaborative sensing,
 and allow for scalable coordination in complex,
 uncertain environments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In marine and aerial logistics,
 the challenges of multi-robot communication and coordination take on new dimensions due to environmental variability,
 connectivity constraints,
 and the physical dynamics of the platforms.
 Autonomous surface vessels (ASVs) and unmanned underwater vehicles (UUVs),
 for instance,
 often operate in GPS-denied or communication-limited environments,
 relying heavily on intermittent data links,
 acoustic communication,
 or pre-planned coordination strategies.
 Similarly,
 drone-based logistics systems must contend with regulatory constraints,
 airspace coordination,
 and short-range radio or LTE/5G-based communication,
 especially in urban or remote areas.
 These platforms are particularly sensitive to latency,
 signal degradation,
 and line-of-sight limitations,
 which places added importance on autonomy at the edge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compared to terrestrial ground robots —
 which often benefit from stable terrain,
 consistent connectivity (e.g.,
 Wi-Fi or mesh networks),
 and easier access to power —
 marine and aerial fleets demand more energy-aware and fault-tolerant coordination strategies.
 For instance,
 in drone delivery networks,
 researchers are exploring dynamic re-routing,
 decentralized path planning,
 and adaptive swarm behaviours to respond to weather disruptions or unexpected obstacles.
 In marine logistics,
 multi-vessel fleets are increasingly coordinated using time-synchronized behaviors or adaptive convoy strategies,
 balancing communication load with mission accuracy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current research trajectory is moving toward resilient,
 hybrid systems that integrate high-level centralized planning with low-level distributed autonomy,
 applicable across domains.
 This cross-pollination of techniques from ground,
 aerial,
 and marine robotics is informing the development of more general-purpose coordination frameworks —
 ones that can adaptively scale,
 function across communication regimes,
 and ensure continuity of operation in real-world conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Real-Time Map Updates and Replanning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In dynamic and unstructured environments,
 such as those encountered during search and rescue,
 exploration,
 or logistics missions,
 the ability for a multi-robot system to update its environmental understanding in real time is crucial.
 Static maps,
 although useful for initial navigation,
 quickly become obsolete as robots discover new obstacles,
 changes in terrain,
 or moving agents.
 As such,
 recent research has focused heavily on methods that enable online mapping and rapid replanning,
 allowing fleets to adapt their trajectories and strategies based on the most up-to-date situational data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the core of this capability is the need for shared,
 scalable,
 and mutable mapping frameworks.
 Octree-based mapping systems,
 such as OctoMap,
 are widely used due to their hierarchical structure and memory efficiency.
 OctoMap’s probabilistic 3D occupancy representation enables the compact storage of large environments while supporting variable resolution—
a critical feature for multi-robot systems where different agents might have varying sensing capabilities or operational priorities.
 However,
 a key challenge remains in fusing multiple OctoMaps or submaps generated by different agents.
 The problem lies in aligning coordinate frames,
 managing overlapping updates,
 and mitigating drift errors in robot odometry.
 Some recent work explores feature-matching and probabilistic fusion approaches to achieve consistent merging of 3D maps from heterogeneous agents,
 though this remains an active area of research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond OctoMaps,
 real-time updates also require systems capable of distinguishing between static,
 dynamic,
 and unknown regions of the map.
 This is especially important for environments with moving obstacles,
 such as humans,
 vehicles,
 or other robots.
 Truncated Signed Distance Fields (TSDFs) and Voxel Hashing have been proposed as alternatives to traditional occupancy grids,
 particularly in visual SLAM and 3D reconstruction,
 due to their ability to represent surfaces implicitly and handle partial observations more robustly.
 Additionally,
 hybrid systems that combine elevation maps (useful for ground robots) with semantic labels or appearance-based maps (e.g.,
 RTAB-Map,
 SkiMap) are being explored to enrich spatial representations with contextual information,
 thereby improving navigation decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replanning algorithms must work hand-in-hand with mapping to maintain mission success.
 When a robot detects a previously unknown obstacle or terrain deformation,
 its existing path may become suboptimal or even infeasible.
 Real-time replanning,
 particularly in multi-robot systems,
 must not only adjust individual trajectories but do so while preserving global coordination and avoiding inter-robot conflicts.
 Algorithms such as D* Lite,
 Anytime Dynamic A*,
 and incremental RRT variants are commonly used for local replanning,
 while global task reassignment may involve centralized or decentralized optimization depending on the communication infrastructure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore,
 in multi-agent systems,
 the latency of map updates and the consistency of shared world models become critical.
 Delays in communication or discrepancies between local maps can lead to conflicting decisions,
 collisions,
 or task duplication.
 Some systems address this through periodic global map fusion,
 while others use consensus-based protocols or blockchain-inspired data validation to maintain consistency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary,
 real-time map updates and replanning are foundational to safe,
 adaptive,
 and scalable multi-robot operation.
 Future research must continue addressing challenges in efficient map fusion,
 semantic and temporal map layering,
 and robust distributed planning under communication and computational constraints.
 This will be especially crucial for applications involving heterogeneous fleets,
 where differing sensory modalities and mobility types require flexible and context-aware integration of mapping and planning processes.
\end_layout

