\begin_layout Section
Task Allocation and Decision-Making
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While risk quantification methods such as Lambda fields provide powerful insight into the physical and operational challenges a robot might encounter,
 their true utility is only realised when they inform higher-level decisions —
 particularly task allocation and mission planning.
 In multi-robot systems,
 especially heterogeneous fleets operating in high-stakes environments like disaster zones,
 it is critical that tasks are not assigned purely based on availability or proximity.
 Instead,
 they must be allocated with an awareness of the robot’s capability,
 the task’s urgency,
 and the environmental risk surrounding both the agent and its intended goal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traditionally,
 task allocation has relied on cost-based models such as the Hungarian algorithm or market-based auction frameworks,
 where robots "bid" for tasks based on estimated completion costs.
 These systems often assume homogeneous risk perception across all agents —
 an assumption that breaks down quickly in real-world scenarios involving terrain-sensitive locomotion (e.g.,
 tracked UGVs vs.
 drones) or domain-specific hazards (e.g.,
 underwater currents for UUVs vs.
 signal loss for UAVs).
 By integrating Lambda field-based risk metrics,
 each agent can carry its own spatially varying risk map,
 allowing for more nuanced comparisons between robots operating in the same area but facing very different challenges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A practical application of this integration is in computing the expected risk for a specific robot–task pair as the cumulative risk encountered along the robot’s planned trajectory.
 This risk can be expressed as a spatial integral over the Lambda field:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Expected Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
β allow weighting of risk tolerance versus mission urgency,
 which can be adjusted dynamically based on available resources or operator input.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover,
 in dynamic environments where conditions evolve —
 such as in SAR missions during aftershocks or flooding —
 Lambda fields can be continuously updated based on new sensory data.
 This enables a risk-aware reallocation strategy,
 where tasks are not static but re-evaluated as environmental risk distributions shift.
 Robots that initially won a task may be reassigned if another unit becomes more suitable due to a safer path or lower expected cost.
 This kind of responsiveness is critical in time-sensitive and high-risk missions where early decisions based on outdated maps could lead to inefficiencies or even mission failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Heterogeneous fleets,
 by nature,
 require even deeper integration of risk into decision-making.
 For example,
 a terrain type that poses minimal risk to a drone may be nearly impassable to a wheeled ground robot.
 Thus,
 Lambda fields must not only inform task assignment,
 but do so in a robot-specific way,
 where risk is computed as a function of both the agent’s locomotion characteristics and its remaining resources (e.g.,
 battery,
 payload capacity,
 sensor quality).
 This enables planners to allocate tasks not just to robots that can complete them,
 but to those that are statistically the most likely to succeed —
 a distinction that becomes vital in uncertain and resource-limited operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In essence,
 Lambda fields offer more than just a physical mapping of risk.
 When fused with utility models and decision-making architectures,
 they allow for robust,
 interpretable,
 and flexible task allocation strategies that respond intelligently to both agent capabilities and real-time environmental conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simulating multi-robot systems is crucial for testing algorithms,
 optimising fleet coordination,
 and evaluating real-world deployment feasibility.
 Various simulation platforms have been developed,
 each catering to different requirements such as physics accuracy,
 scalability,
 sensor integration,
 and human interaction.
 This section reviews prominent simulators used in multi-robotics,
 including Gazebo,
 Isaac Sim,
 Unreal Engine,
 Unity,
 and CoppeliaSim,
 assessing their strengths and limitations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gazebo has long been the go-to simulator for ROS-based robotic systems,
 offering tight integration with ROS 2,
 support for sensor simulation,
 and modular plugin-based architecture.
 It has been widely used for mobile robots,
 manipulators,
 and UAVs.
 However,
 its CPU-based physics engine and limited scalability present challenges for simulating large multi-robot fleets.
 Gazebo also lacks GPU acceleration,
 making it less suitable for real-time AI training and large-scale distributed simulations (Koenig & Howard,
 2004).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Isaac Sim,
 developed by NVIDIA,
 leverages Omniverse and PhysX 5 for GPU-accelerated physics,
 making it one of the most powerful platforms for simulating multi-robot fleets.
 Unlike Gazebo,
 Isaac Sim supports ROS 2 natively,
 integrates AI reinforcement learning pipelines,
 and offers photorealistic rendering with RTX support.
 Additionally,
 it facilitates cloud-based simulations,
 allowing large-scale fleet testing with distributed computing.
 Isaac Sim’s ability to simulate high-fidelity sensors (LiDAR,
 depth cameras,
 stereo vision) and integrate with OctoMaps for 3D mapping makes it a strong contender for autonomous robotic fleets (Makoviychuk et al.,
 2021).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unreal Engine has emerged as a powerful alternative for simulating large-scale environments due to its advanced rendering capabilities,
 flexible physics engine,
 and real-time visualisation tools.
 It has been particularly useful for human-robot interaction (HRI),
 AR/VR simulations,
 and urban-scale robotics applications.
 Unlike Isaac Sim,
 Unreal Engine does not natively support GPU-accelerated physics for multi-robotics but can handle massive environments efficiently (Shah et al.,
 2018).
 However,
 its ROS 2 integration requires third-party plugins like AirSim,
 making it less straightforward for robotics research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unity provides game-engine-level scalability and excellent visualization tools,
 making it ideal for applications requiring UI-heavy interfaces,
 digital twins,
 and large-scale virtual environments.
 Unity supports ROS 2 through its ROS-TCP Connector,
 but its physics engine is less accurate than Isaac Sim or Gazebo.
 However,
 its ability to handle real-time simulations with large numbers of robots makes it a viable choice for fleet visualisation and urban robotics (Craighead et al.,
 2007).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CoppeliaSim (formerly V-REP) is known for its multi-threaded simulation environment,
 allowing multiple robots to operate independently.
 It provides real-time inverse kinematics,
 physics simulation,
 and support for swarm robotics.
 While it integrates well with ROS 2,
 it lacks GPU acceleration,
 making it less suitable for high-fidelity sensor simulations (Rohmer et al.,
 2013).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the requirements for multi-robot fleet simulation,
 Isaac Sim emerges as the best all-around choice due to its GPU-accelerated physics,
 AI integration,
 and cloud scalability.
 However,
 if the focus is on large-scale world simulations or human-robot interaction,
 Unreal Engine or Unity may be better choices.
 Gazebo remains viable for ROS 2 users,
 but its limitations in physics accuracy and scalability make it less ideal for multi-robot coordination.
 Future research should explore hybrid approaches that combine Isaac Sim’s AI-driven simulations with Unreal Engine’s large-scale visualisation to create next-generation multi-robot simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This research introduces a novel and integrated framework for coordinating fully heterogeneous robotic fleets —
 including aerial,
 aquatic,
 legged,
 wheeled,
 and surface agents —
 within high-risk,
 real-world disaster environments.
 The key contributions are outlined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Unified Traversability Risk Assessment Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A centralised framework is developed that quantitatively assesses terrain risk using a probabilistic model.
 It fuses both sensor-based and map-based metrics to evaluate environmental suitability for each locomotion type.
 This approach accounts for physical and operational constraints,
 enabling consistent comparisons of terrain traversability across all agent types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Extension of Lambda Fields to Multi-Robot Decision-Making
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work adapts the Lambda field framework —
 traditionally applied to individual robot path planning —
 for use in fleet-level coordination.
 By treating risk as a physically meaningful,
 spatially distributed field,
 it enables heterogeneous agents to make informed decisions based on their locomotion-specific vulnerabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Risk-Aware Task Allocation and Mission Planning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A mission planning algorithm is proposed that dynamically allocates tasks based on agents' capabilities,
 resource states (e.g.,
 energy reserves),
 and environmental risk distributions.
 This ensures that each task is matched to the robot most likely to succeed,
 improving operational robustness and responsiveness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 Real-Time 3D Map Fusion and Replanning Pipeline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hybrid map merging approach is implemented,
 combining global feature matching with local ICP-based refinement.
 This strategy improves localisation and map consistency among agents operating in GPS-denied or spatially disconnected environments.
 The system supports dynamic replanning in response to environmental change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 Simulation-Based Validation in Disaster Scenarios
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The framework is validated using high-fidelity simulations across urban,
 rural,
 and hybrid disaster landscapes.
 Leveraging platforms like Isaac Sim and OctoMap,
 the evaluation demonstrates the framework’s effectiveness in terrain-aware decision-making,
 risk modelling,
 and coordination under dynamic,
 uncertain conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together,
 these contributions address major challenges in contemporary multi-robot research,
 particularly the lack of frameworks capable of unifying all locomotion types within a risk-aware,
 dynamically adaptive decision-making architecture.
 The work not only introduces technical innovations but also proposes a scalable,
 mission-relevant solution for future real-world deployments in disaster response and exploration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The literature reviewed throughout this chapter establishes a clear need for a unified,
 risk-aware coordination strategy for heterogeneous multi-robot systems.
 Existing approaches have made significant strides in dual- or tri-locomotion coordination,
 path planning,
 mapping,
 and fleet control;
 however,
 they often operate within narrow domains and rely on simplifying assumptions unsuited to real-world,
 high-stakes environments like SAR.
 This research seeks to build on and extend these foundations by introducing a cohesive framework that can support true heterogeneity,
 dynamic replanning,
 and risk-based task distribution in realistic terrain.
 The following chapter presents the formal problem formulation underpinning this framework,
 laying out the assumptions,
 mathematical models,
 and performance objectives that guide the development of the system.
\end_layout

